.SS "GUEST STORAGE"
By default, chyves uses ZFS volumes as guest storage backing\. Each volume is named disk{n} and is attached to the guest via an emulated AHCI controller\. On all hosts, 8 ahci\-hd devices are supported per PCI slot\. On certain hosts, up to 32 ahci devices can be attached per PCI slot\. See global property \'consolidate_bhyve_pci_devices\' for details\.
.
.P
There is limited support for raw file backed guest storage\. This is a manual process and there are not any chyves commands that create, modify, or delete these raw image files\. \fBAll files\fR in the \'img/\' folder and child folders are attached to the guest on start\. To have independent snapshots for each raw image, create a child datasets under \fB<pool>/chyves/guests/<guest>/img\fR, this has an advantage over ZFS volumes as there is no refreservation cost associated with the snapshots\. The command \fBchyves info\fR reports the raw image files and size\. To create a sparse raw image run:
.
.P
\fBtruncate \-s 16G /chyves/<pool>/guests/<guest>/img/<image\-name>\fR
.
.SH "LOGS"
All logs entries are stored on the primary pool under \fB/chyves/<primary\-pool>/chyves/logs\fR with the dataset\'s compression turned on\. The file are separated on a monthly basis using a \fBYYYYMM\.log\fR file name\. The log entries use the ISO 8601 date format for monitoring tools\. There is a separate log file on a per guest basis, however at this time not all guest events are recorded to this file, however these events \fIare\fR recorded in the global logs regardless\.
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

2016\-07\-09T21:27:00+0000 \- [2] \- Mimicking tap50 interface for g10\.
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.P
The logs are dash delimited with leading and trailing single spaces\. The first field indicates the time in ISO 8601 format, \'2016\-07\-09T21:27:00+0000\' in the example above\. The second field is the \'stdout_level\', \'2\' in the example above\. The third field is the log event, \'Mimicking tap50 interface for g10\.\' in the example above\. See the \fIGlobal Configuration Properties\fR section below for more information on what \'stdout_level\' does\.
.
.SH "NETWORK"
The network mode is set by the global setting \'\fBnetwork_design_mode\fR\' and determines how chyves handles network devices for the guests\. The two modes are \'\fBauto\fR\' and \'\fBsystem\fR\', both modes are discussed below\.
.
.P
VALE support is experimentally provided as a proof of concept\. VALE support is not widely implemented and is feature limited at it\'s current development stage\. To use VALE requires that \'device netmap\' be compiled into the kernel and that \'vale\-ctl\' be compiled from \'/usr/src/tools/tools/netmap\' and moved to $PATH directory\. VALE natively support em(4), igb(4), ixgbe(4), and re(4)\. Other NICs must use emulation which may reduce performance\. See netmap(4) for more information\. VALE interfaces are added to a guest the same way a tap interface is added using: \'\fBchyves network add vale{n}[:{p}]\fR\' where {n} is the vale switch you want to use and optionally :{p} specifies the port on that switch\. Specifying a port is not recommended\. VALE interfaces are clever in that the interface is commonly shared between other guests connecting to that \'virtual\' VALE switch\. Two guests using \'vale0\' will be connected to the same virtual switch\.
.
.P
Hosts after a certain commit support Intel e1000 emulation as an alternative to using virtio\-net\. This can be utilized by setting \'bhyve_net_type\' to \'e1000\', see guest property for details\.
.
.SS "AUTO DESIGN NETWORK MODE"
By default, chyves is configured to manage the complete network design layout\. chyves keeps track of which physical, tap, and vlan interfaces are associated with which bridges, and which tap and VALE interfaces are associated with which guests\. Upon starting a guest these designs are checked, verified, and then created if not existing\. To manage the network design using this method, use the \'chyves network\' commands to create the associations and \'chyves list bridges\' for an overview\.
.
.P
On a fresh simple installation, the only command needed is \'chyves network bridge0 attach em0\'\. This tells chyves to associate the interface \'em0\' with the default bridge\. To change the default bridge, the command would be \'chyves network bridge64 default\' to set \'bridge64\' as the default\. All tap interfaces created for guests are then associated with the bridge set in defaults\.
.
.P
As indicated above, tap interfaces are attached to a bridge, which optionally can be attached to a physical or vlan interface\. If the bridge is not associated with a physical or vlan interface, the bridge must be put into \'private\' mode\. This is done by running \'chyves network bridge64 private\'\. A private bridge allows sensitive traffic to transverse the bridge without the possibility of traffic being monitored from an outside network\. A private bridge can also use pf(4) for NAT capabilities but this is not built into chyves\.
.
.SS "SYSTEM DESIGN NETWORK MODE"
The \'system\' mode assumes the user will correctly create and configure all devices on the host system, including the tap devices\. No checks are ran to test connectivity and chyves simply attaches tap or VALE interfaces to the guest as configured in the \'net_ifaces\' property\.
.
.P
Converting from \'system\' to \'auto\' will not automatically start to work\. Each device will need to be manually associated with each other\.
.
.SH "PROPERTIES"
There are four types of chyves properties: global configuration properties, pool properties, per\-guest properties, and default guest properties\. Each is stored in a file in the chyves dataset hierarchy\. \fBIt is not recommended to directly edit the \'*\.cfg\' files, this is because there are no filters to stop typos, warn for incorrect property names, or invalid values\.\fR The filter is only applied when running the \'chyves \fIguest\fR set\' command and not rechecked when pulling the values from the files\.
.
.P
Also certain actions are triggered when setting certain properties\. For example, setting the \'\fBtemplate\fR\' guest property will set or unset the \fIreadonly\fR flag on the ZFS dataset\.
.
.P
The pool configuration is stored in a file at \'/chyves/\fIpool\fR/\.config/pool\.cfg\'\. On the primary pool there is also a file in the same directory called \'global\.cfg\', this contains the global settings for chyves\.
.
.P
The \'dataset_role\' setting is used to store the role of that pool containing the chyves datasets\. Valid values are primary, secondary, and offline\. Only one \'primary\' dataset can be configured per system\. The primary dataset is the only dataset that contains the ISO and firmware resources\. Only the primary pool has guest defaults configuration file\. These defaults are referenced when setting properties for new guests\. The primary pool is also where new guests are created when the [\fIpool\fR] argument is not declared with \'chyves create\' command\. All other active pools are set to the "secondary" role\. Pools set to the \'offline\' role are left untouched and is a good role to put a local replicated backup\. The primary pool is critical to the operation of chyves, without a primary pool set, only the \'dataset\' sub\-command are permitted to run\. The first pool setup on the system is the primary pool\. This can be changed later with \'chyves dataset \fIpool\fR promote\'\.
.
.SS "Pool Properties"
These properties keeps track of the version of the dataset and the role\. With multiple pools, defined per\-pool roles are necessary\. This is defined through the use of a dataset called \'\fIpool\fR/chyves/\.config\' where the pool specific properties (\fBpool\.cfg\fR) are stored\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBdataset_role={primary|secondary|offline}\fR
.
.IP
\fBManaged through \'chyves dataset\' commands\.\fR
.
.IP
Vital in multi\-pool configurations, each role type has different characteristics as explained below:
.
.IP
\fBprimary\fR \- Pools in this role are utilized exclusively for the following purposes: Store ISO and Firmware resources\. Reference point for global properties\. New guest are defaulted to be created on this pool unless otherwise specified as a property for \'chyves create\'\. Only one ZFS pool can be in the primary role per system and is the only role for single zpool configurations\.
.
.IP
\fBsecondary\fR \- Pools in this role are utilized for storing other active guests not stored on the primary ZFS pool\.
.
.IP
\fBoffline\fR \- Pools in this role are not utilized, this role is intended for backup\. Guests on these pools are omitted from all subcommands\. To further prevent action on \'offline\' pools, the dataset is renamed to \'chyves_offline\' which chyves will completely ignore\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBpool_version={dataset\-version}\fR
.
.IP
\fBManaged through \'chyves dataset\' commands\.\fR
.
.IP
This property indicates the current version of the chyves pool\. This an upgrade mechanism to ensure the dataset and it\'s child datasets contain the correct architecture\. The command \'chyves dataset \fIpool\fR upgrade\' brings a dataset incrementally to the latest version when there is a discrepancy between the dataset version and the chyves version\. A check is ran before execution to ensure the version of the pool is compatible with the version of chyves\.
.
.IP "" 0
.
.SS "Global Configuration Properties"
These properties control the behavior of chyves\.
.
.P
Many of these properties are not recommended to be changed directly unless the scope of their impact is understood or when managed through subcommands such as \'\fBchyves network\fR\'\. The preferred management method is given on the first line after each property in bold text\.
.
.P
Usage:
.
.P
\fBchyves global set <property>=<value>\fR
.
.P
\fBchyves list global [<pool>]\fR
.
.P
Properties:
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBauto_load_kernel_mods\fR={yes|no}
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
When set to "yes", chyves will load the kernel modules necessary for guests\. When set to \'no\', chyves will simply check if the modules are loaded and exit with a message if not loaded\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBbridge{n}_phy_attach\fR={\fIinterface\fR|private}
.
.IP
\fBManaged through \'chyves network\' commands\.\fR
.
.IP
This property contains a physical or vlan interface name for a bridge to belong\. When set to \'private\' the bridge is not joined with a outside network\.
.
.IP
Example values:
.
.IP
\fBbridge0_attach=em0\fR
.
.IP
\fBbridge10_phy_attach=vlan52\fR
.
.IP
\fBbridge512_phy_attach=private\fR
.
.IP
Usage:
.
.IP
\fBchyves network bridge{n} attach {<interface>|private}\fR
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBbridge{n}_tap_members\fR={tap{n}[,tap{n},tap{n}]}
.
.IP
\fBManaged through \'chyves network\' commands\.\fR
.
.IP
This property is a comma separated list of the tap members for bridge{n}, where {n} is the interface number\. Valid values for {n} are 0 to 32768\. Guests are automatically added to this property using the bridge{n} that is set in \'defaults\' under the \'bridge\' property\.
.
.IP
Examples values:
.
.IP
\fBbridge0_tap_members=tap0\fR
.
.IP
\fBbridge70_tap_members=tap20,tap30\fR
.
.IP
A tap can be moved to another bridge by first removing the tap from the original bridge and adding to the desired bridge\. Use the following command syntax to do this:
.
.IP
\fBchyves network bridge{n} unjoin tap{n}\fR
.
.IP
\fBchyves network bridge{n} join tap{n}\fR
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBcheck_for_updates\fR={off|daily|weekly|monthly|always}
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
This determines how often to check for updates for chyves on the GitHub repository\. The keyword \'always\' means to check every time chyves is ran\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBcheck_for_updates_last_check\fR=YYYYMMDD
.
.IP
\fBManaged internally\.\fR
.
.IP
This contain the date of last check\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBcheck_for_updates_last_check_status\fR={1|0}
.
.IP
\fBManaged internally\.\fR
.
.IP
When set to \'1\' an update is available\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBcheck_for_updates_timeout_seconds\fR={n}
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
This number is used to set the network timeout for fetch(1) before giving up\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBcheck_for_updates_unique_id\fR=UUID
.
.IP
\fBManaged internally\.\fR
.
.IP
This contains a UUID used for identification\. It is set when the primary pool was created\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBconsole_start_offset\fR={integer}
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
This is a compatibility mechanism used to offset the first chyves null console modem number so that a collision are less likely with another application or bhyve front end manager\. The initial default is set to \'50\'\. After the first guests are created, then the next highest console number is used to create the next guest\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBconsolidate_bhyve_pci_devices\fR={no|yes}
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
The default is set to \'no\' as it may have performance implications, however this may be necessary if more than 26 PCI devices are connect to a guest\. This property signals the bhyve string generators to use all PCI functions for similar devices\.
.
.IP
On all hosts, 8 PCI functions can be used per PCI slot\. However, up to 32 ahci\-hd devices can be attached to a single PCI slot for hosts running 12\-CURRENT after commit r302459, 11\-STABLE after commit r304422, or hosts running 10\-STABLE after commit r304420\. Meaning in ideal conditions up to 208 PCI devices can be attached on any host or up to 832 devices on supported hosts\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBdefault_clone_flag\fR
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
Flag to use when cloning a guest and the clone type flag is omitted\. See clone command under \fIGUEST CLONE SUB\-SUB\-COMMAND\fR section\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBdefault_info_flags\fR
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
Flags set here are passed to \'chyves info\' when no flags are used\. See command \'chyves info\' for valid flags\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBdefault_list_flags\fR
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
Flags set here are passed to \'chyves info\' WHEN the command \'chyves list\' is used\. Both commands use the same backend function and \'chyves list\' is kept around for legacy reasons\. See command \'chyves info\' for valid flags\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBdev_mode\fR={off|on|\-xvn}
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable, advanced feature\.\fR
.
.IP
Setting to \'on\' allows for functions to be called direct from the command line using \fBchyves dev\fR\. Using the \fB\-xvn\fR flags instead of the word \fBon\fR will use Bourne\'s \fBset\fR command to turn on special option flags during \fBchyves dev\fR execution\. These flags can be used individually (\-x|\-v|\-n) or combined (\-xv)\. See sh(1)\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBeject_iso_on_n_reboot\fR={n}
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
See same property name under the \fIGuest Properties\fR section below for description of functionality\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBlog_mode\fR={host|guest|dual}
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
Determines the source of information to save in the log files when \'log_to_file\' is set to \'yes\'\. When set to \'guest\' only guest actions are recorded\. When set to \'host\' only actions not involving guests are recorded\. When set to dual, both are recorded\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBlog_to_file\fR={yes|no}
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
Turns on logging to a file\. For general logging the file is saved at \'/chyves/logs/YYYYMM\.log\' and for guests the file is saved at \'/chyves/guests/\fIguest\fR/log/YYYYMM\.log\' or at \'/chyves/\fIpool\fRguests/\fIguest\fR/ log/YYYYMM\.log\'\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBnetwork_design_mode\fR={auto|system}
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
The default is \'auto\', which means chyves manages everything above the physical or vlan Ethernet interface, all the way to the guest\. This is managed through \'chyves network\' commands\. When set to \'system\', chyves only attaches the tap or VALE interfaces to the guest and leaves it to the user to have configured everything else (correctly)\. See \fINETWORK\fR section above\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBrestrict_new_property_names\fR=[off|on]
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable, advanced feature\.\fR
.
.IP
Setting to "on" allows for new properties to be created with \'chyves set\'\. The default is set to "off" to prevent creating new properties due to typos\. Even when set to \'on\' this will not allow a creation of new global or defaults properties\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBstdout_level\fR={0\-3}
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
Determines the amount of output to send to the terminal\. The four numeric settings do the following\. This does not impact the log files\.
.
.IP
\fB0 \- off\fR \- No output
.
.IP
\fB1 \- minimal\fR Sub command action shown
.
.IP
\fB2 \- regular\fR + Each step in the sub command shown
.
.IP
\fB3 \- verbose\fR ++ Outputs bhyve and loader command used\.
.
.IP
\fB4\fR \-\- Never print to screen\. Used in \fB__return*\fR functions that would break even with the value set to \'0\'\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBtap_start_offset\fR={integer}
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
This is a compatibility mechanism used to offset the first chyves tap interface so that a collision is less likely with another application or bhyve front end manager\. The initial default is set to "50", valid values are from 0 to 32767\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBtap_up_by_default\fR={off|on}
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
When set to "yes", the sysctl: net\.link\.tap\.up_on_open is set to "1" when running script\. Default is "on" but it is recommended to set to "off" and update your /boot/loader\.conf to set this sysctl\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBvlan_iface_base_name\fR=\fIvlan_base_name\fR
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
When using a non\-standard vlan naming nomenclature this needs to reflect the change\. The default is "vlan" when using the standard "vlan{n}" naming nomenclature\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBuefi_vnc_port_start_offset\fR={integer}
.
.IP
\fBUser managed and settable\.\fR
.
.IP
This is a compatibility mechanism used to offset the first VNC port used by UEFI guests\. The initial default is set to "5900", valid values are from 1 to 65536\.
.
.IP "" 0
.
.SS "Guest Properties"
These are properties used by chyves to specify the properties to pass to bhyve, grub\-bhyve, and chyves itself when starting a guest\. Changing these values on a running guest will not yield any change until the guest is completely stop and then started again\.
.
.P
Usage:
.
.P
\fBchyves <guest> get <property>\fR
.
.P
\fBchyves <guest> get all\fR
.
.P
\fBchyves list properties\fR
.
.P
\fBchyves list <property>\fR
.
.P
\fBchyves <guest>|MG|all set <property1>=<value> [<property2>=<value>] [<property3>=<value>]\fR
.
.P
\fBchyves <guest>|MG|all set <property1>=<value> [<property2>=<value>] [<property3>=<value>] [<guest2> [<property1>=<value>] [<property2>=<value>]]\fR
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBaudio_play\fR=\fIaudio\-playing\-dev\fR
.
.IP
This requires a patched bhyve binary from the GSoC 2016 project HDAudioEmulationForBhyve\.
.
.IP
This property describes an audio playback devices on the host used for audio output from a guest\. Eg\. /dev/dsp0
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBaudio_rec\fR=\fIaudio\-recording\-dev\fR
.
.IP
This requires a patched bhyve binary from the GSoC 2016 project HDAudioEmulationForBhyve\.
.
.IP
This property describes an audio recording devices on the host used for recording audio from a guest\. Eg\. /dev/dsp0
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBbargs\fR
.
.IP
For advanced users to pass additional flags directly to \fBbhyve\fR\. See bhyve(8) for complete list of flag options\. To find out which flags are used when starting a specific guest, turn on global configuration \'stdout_level\' to \'3\' or check the global log file\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBbhyveload_flags\fR
.
.IP
For advanced users to pass additional flags directly to \fBbhyveload\fR\. This is primarily intended to pass \'\-e\' flags for environment variables\. See bhyveload(8) for a complete list of flag options\. To find out which flags are used when starting a specific guest, turn on global configuration \'stdout_level\' to \'3\' or check the global log file\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBbhyve_disk_type\fR={virtio\-blk|ahci\-hd}
.
.IP
Sets the method to attach ZFS volumes and disk images to the guest\. Most guests do not support Virt\-IO block devices without installing drivers at installation\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBbhyve_net_type\fR={virtio\-net|e1000}
.
.IP
Sets the method to attach tap interfaces to the guest\. Intel e1000 emulation is available on hosts on 12\-CURRENT after commit r302504, 11\-STABLE after commit r304424, and on 10\-STABLE after commit r304425\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBcpu\fR={n}
.
.IP
Assigns {n} number of CPU cores to a guest, up to 16\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBchyves_guest_version\fR=\fIMMmm\fR
.
.IP
\fBManaged through \'chyves \fIguest\fR upgrade\' command\.\fR
.
.IP
Used to ensure the guest contains latest properties when moved between hosts on different versions of chyves\. "MM" signifies the major version as an integer and "mm" as the minor version as an integer\. Changes to the major version require an upgrade via \'chyves \fIguest\fR upgrade\' because a guest property value format has changed or a new required property was added\. Differences in the minor version do no require an upgrade but may not have full functionality\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBdescription\fR="\fIINSERT BRIEF DESCRIPTION\fR"
.
.IP
Used to describe guest\. Use double quotes when description contains spaces\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBeject_iso_on_n_reboot\fR={n}
.
.IP
This property determines if and when to eject the optical media when installing an OS\. By default this is set to \'1\' because most *nix systems install on the first boot\. A guest running off a live CD should be turned to \'0\' for off\. Windows systems should be set to \'2\' or greater during initial installation\.
.
.IP
There is a global property which shares the same name and has the same functionality\. The global property is used if not set on the guest\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBloader\fR={bhyveload|uefi|grub\-bhyve}
.
.IP
Tells which loader to use to boot guest\. \fBbhyveload\fR is for FreeBSD based guests, \fBuefi\fR is used for UEFI based guests, and \fBgrub\-bhyve\fR is used for all other guests\.
.
.IP
When setting a guest to use the \fBuefi\fR loader, some \fBuefi_*\fR properties are populated\. One of these properties is \fBuefi_firmware\fR which is required for guests to start\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBnet_ifaces\fR=tap{n}|vale{n}[:{p}]
.
.IP
\fBManaged through \'chyves network\' commands when \'network_design_mode\' is set to \'auto\'\.\fR
.
.IP
\fBUser settable when \'network_design_mode\' is set to \'system\'\.\fR
.
.IP
Stores which tap and VALE interfaces are assigned to a guest\. Where {n} is a unique interface number\. Taps are process locked and can not be shared simultaneously by multiple guests\. Multiple devices are stored using commas as delimiters\.
.
.IP
VALE interface names must be vale{n}[:{p}] where {n} can be alpha\-numeric up to 9 characters long\. Optionally a port can be specified where :{p} starts with a separating colon and either a single alphabetical character or a number 0\-9999\.
.
.IP
Usage:
.
.IP
\fBchyves network <guest> add {tap|tap{n}|vale{s}[:{p}]}\fR
.
.IP
\fBchyves network <guest> add {tap|tap{n}} bridge{n}\fR
.
.IP
\fBchyves network <guest> remove {tap{n}|vale{s}[:{p}]}\fR
.
.IP
See \fINETWORK SUB\-COMMANDS\fR section for complete list of commands to manage this property\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBnotes\fR="\fIINSERT FURTHER NOTES\fR"
.
.IP
Used to further describe guests\. Use double quotes when description contains spaces\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBos\fR=\fIoperating\-system\fR
.
.IP
Used to determine the properties to use for the \fBgrub\.cfg\fR and \fBdevice\.map\fR files when the \fBloader\fR property is set to \fBgrub\-bhyve\fR\.
.
.IP
Supported values are \'arch\', \'centos6\', \'centos7\', \'coreos\', \'coreossecure\', \'custom\', \'debian\', \'d8lvm\', \'default\', \'gentoo\', \'netbsd\', \'openbsd\', or \'vyos\'\. Any other values are invalid and the settings for \'\fBdefault\fR\' are used as a generic catch\-all\.
.
.IP
When \'coreos\' is used, the flag \'coreos\.autologin\' is used to bypass authentication for the console\. When \'coreossecure\' is used, the console requires a username and password\.
.
.IP
When \'openbsd\' is used, the media must maintain the project\'s installation media name format of \'installXX\.iso\' or \'cdXX\.iso\', where \'XX\' is the numeric release\.
.
.IP
Using \fBcustom\fR relies on the user to manually create the \fBgrub\.cfg\fR and \fBdevice\.map\fR files in the guest directory \fB/chyves/<pool>/guests/<guest>\fR\.
.
.IP
Example:
.
.IP
For an OpenBSD guest "obsd59" located in \fB/chyves/kubota/obsd59/\fR and an install ISO in \fB/chyves/dozer/ISO/install59\.iso/\fR, your files will look like this:
.
.IP
\fBdevice\.map\fR file:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

(hd0) /dev/zvol/kubota/chyves/obsd59/disk0
(cd0) /chyves/dozer/ISO/install59\.iso/install59\.iso
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.IP
\fBgrub\.cfg\fR file for installation:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

kopenbsd \-h com0 (cd0)/5\.9/amd64/bsd\.rd
boot
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.IP
\fBgrub\.cfg\fR file after installation is complete:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

kopenbsd \-h com0 \-r sd0a (hd0,openbsd1)/bsd
boot
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.IP
The \fBchyves\fR project welcomes any OS submissions to help other users from re\-discovering leg work done by others\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBpcidev_{n}\fR={bhyve\-pci\-dev}
.
.IP
This is an advance feature and assumes you have read bhyve(8) AND understood it\. This property does NOT have a complete input verification suite or complete host support verification\.
.
.IP
This property attaches a bhyve PCI device to the guest\. The \'{n}\' is completely arbitrary number and is only a matter of the order of attachment\. \'{bhyve\-pci\-dev}\' is the bhyve PCI device to attach\. See bhyve(8) for a complete list or below for common uses\.
.
.IP
\fBchyves\fR attaches each custom PCI device alone on the PCI bus, except for pass\-through devices\.
.
.IP
To create a virtio RNG, the command would be
.
.IP
\fBchyves <guest> set pcidev_0=virtio\-rnd\fR
.
.IP
To create a permanently attached optical media device using a chyves ISO resource where "cd\.iso" is the ISO name, the command would be:
.
.IP
\fBchyves <guest> set pcidev_1=ahci\-cd,/chyves/<primary\-pool>/ISO/cd\.iso/cd\.iso\fR
.
.IP
To create a sparse 16G disk and attach, the commands would be:
.
.IP
\fBtruncate \-s 16G /chyves/<pool>/guests/<guest>/01\.img\fR
.
.IP
\fBchyves <guest> set pcidev_2=ahci\-hd,/chyves/<pool>/guests/<guest>/01\.img[,block\-options]\fR
.
.IP
Although not recommended, a tap interface can be manually attached using this command:
.
.IP
\fBchyves <guest> set pcidev_3=virtio\-net,tap10\fR
.
.IP
\&\.\.\.using Intel e1000 emulation (only 12\-CURRENT hosts):
.
.IP
\fBchyves <guest> set pcidev_5=e1000,tap10\fR
.
.IP
\&\.\.\.with an associated mac address:
.
.IP
\fBchyves <guest> set pcidev_4=virtio\-net,tap10,mac=58:9C:FC:00:00:00\fR
.
.IP
PCI pass\-through devices which share the same physical PCI slot number on the host also will share the same virtual physical slot number in the guest\. This is due to the potential for kernel panics on certain devices such as Fiber Channel PCI cards\. Keep in mind, only eight PCI functions can be assigned to a virtual physical slot in \fBbhyve\fR, additional devices are ignored\. To set a PCI pass\-through device use the follow commands, where \'6\' and \'7\' are arbitrary values and \'9/0/0\' and \'9/0/1\' is the PCI bus/slot/function device triplet\.
.
.IP
\fBchyves <guest> set pcidev_6=passthru,9/0/0\fR
.
.IP
\fBchyves <guest> set pcidev_7=passthru,9/0/1\fR
.
.IP
To get the PCI triplet on the host, run:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

root@bhost:~ # pciconf \-lv | grep \-A4 \-E \'^ppt\'
ppt0@pci0:9:0:0: class=0x0c0400 card=0x01461077 chip=0x24321077 rev=0x02 hdr=0x00
vendor     = \'QLogic Corp\.\'
device     = \'ISP2432\-based 4Gb Fibre Channel to PCI Express HBA\'
class      = serial bus
subclass   = Fibre Channel
ppt1@pci0:9:0:1: class=0x0c0400 card=0x01461077 chip=0x24321077 rev=0x02 hdr=0x00
vendor     = \'QLogic Corp\.\'
device     = \'ISP2432\-based 4Gb Fibre Channel to PCI Express HBA\'
class      = serial bus
subclass   = Fibre Channel
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.IP
Normally the device in the example above would use the \fBisp(4)\fR drivers\. However, the devices need to be using the \fBppt\fR drivers\. In this context, the \fBppt\fR drivers tell the host to ignore the device as it will be pass\-through to a virtualized guest\. To get a PCI device to load the \fBppt\fR drivers instead of it\'s normal drivers, edit the \fB/boot/loader\.conf\fR file to contain the PCI triplet of each device in the \fBpptdevs\fR directive\. The following is consistent with our examples above:
.
.IP "" 4
.
.nf

pptdevs="9/0/0 9/0/1"
.
.fi
.
.IP "" 0
.
.IP
A reboot is necessary after editing the \fB/boot/loader\.conf\fR\.
.
.IP
The \'\fB\-S\fR\' flag \fImust\fR be appended to the current \'\fBbargs\fR\' guest property to wire the guest memory for PCI pass\-through to work\.
.
.IP
To remove a \fBpcidev_{n}\fR from a guest run: \fBchyves <guest>|MG|all unset <pcidev_{n}>\fR\.
.
.IP
VGA/GPU Passthrough has not been reported to work\. chyves issue #3 on GitHub was opened to document success and failures of bhyve passthrough of VGA/GPU devices\. Check there for the latest status\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBram\fR={n}[S]
.
.IP
{n} is the number of bytes and [S] is the size denomination in "K" kilobytes, "M" megabytes, "G" gigabytes, or "T" terabytes\. Megabytes are assumed if no suffix is given\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBrcboot\fR={n}
.
.IP
Any non\-zero number tells chyves to start the guest upon host boot when the \'chyves_enable=YES\' directive is used in \'/etc/rc\.conf\'\. The integer represents the boot priority where the highest numbered guest is started first\. Using \'0\' disables starting on host boot\. If multiple guest share the same priority number, then those guests are started alphabetically\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBrevert_to_snapshot\fR=@snapshot\-name
.
.IP
Describes the snapshot to revert to based on the handling method specified in \'revert_to_snapshot_method\'\. If this property is blank but a method is specified, then the latest snapshot is used\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBrevert_to_snapshot_method\fR={both|off|reboot|start}
.
.IP
Prior to starting and/or rebooting, a guest can be reverted to a previous snapshot state\. This is helpful for guests that get modified outside of specification such as frequently compromised web server or VDI instances\. Setting to \'start\' only reverts the guest when starting the guest, \'reboot\' only on reboots, \'both\' for both starts and restarts, and \'off\' to disable this feature on the guest\.
.
.IP
The snapshot rollback impacts the entire dataset including guest properties\. The guest properties are reloaded after the rollback to ensure there is a consistent guest state\. See the \fBsnapshot rollback\fR command under the \fIGUEST SNAPSHOT SUB\-SUB\-COMMANDS\fR section for details on what actions are taken during a rollback\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBserial\fR=nmdm{n}
.
.IP
Attaches null modem console\. {n} must be a unique number and can not be shared between started guests\. A unique number is given on creation\. Not recommended to be changed and can never be changed while guest is running\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBtap{n}_mac\fR={xx:xx:xx:yy:yy:yy}
.
.IP
Where {n} is the tap interface number to assign the specified MAC address to be attached to the network adapter inside the guest OS\. The MAC address is an ASCII string in ethers(5) format\.
.
.IP
Usage:
.
.IP
\fBchyves <guest> set tap10_mac=58:9C:FC:00:00:00\fR
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBtemplate\fR={yes|no}
.
.IP
When set to \'yes\' chyves will not start the guest\. The guest\'s datasets are set to readonly so no changes can be made until set back to \'no\'\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBuefi_console_output\fR={vnc|serial}
.
.IP
When set to "serial", a UEFI guest will use the standard serial interface\. Guests set to "vnc" will use a VNC connection on supported hosts\. VNC output is experimental and introduced to bhyve in May 2016\. VNC support requires at least 11\-CURRENT (r300097) or later, a modified bhyve binary with graphics support, and the UEFI firmware "BHYVE_UEFI_20160526\.fd"\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBuefi_firmware\fR=\fIfirmware\-resource\-name\fR
.
.IP
UEFI firmware bootrom file used to boot UEFI guests\. These are available in Peter Grehan\'s public FreeBSD file directory or sysutils/uefi\-edk2\-bhyve\. The value must be the exact name as displayed in \'chyves list firmware\'\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBuefi_vnc_client\fR={custom|freerdp|print|vncviewer}
.
.IP
This stores the preferred VNC client used to start a session with the guest properties pre\-populated\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBuefi_vnc_client_custom_cmd\fR
.
.IP
This contains the command to start the VNC client when \'uefi_vnc_client\' is set to \'custom\'\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBuefi_vnc_ip\fR=x\.x\.x\.x
.
.IP
Specifies the IP for the host to bind\-to for VNC connections for the guest\. The default is "0\.0\.0\.0" which binds to all IPs on the host\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBuefi_vnc_mouse_type\fR=ps2|usb3
.
.IP
This property is only used when the property "uefi_console_output" is set to "vnc"\. When set to "ps2" a PS/2 mouse is connected to the guest\. When set "usb3" a USB 3\.0 tablet is emulated which provides much better mouse performance but is only supported on newer guest OSes\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBuefi_vnc_pause_until_client_connect\fR={on|off}
.
.IP
When set to "on" the guest will wait to boot until a VNC client connects\. This is helpful for installations requiring a key press within a short timing window\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBuefi_vnc_port\fR={n}
.
.IP
Specifies the port for the host to listen on for VNC connections for the guest\. Valid values are from 1 to 65536\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBuefi_vnc_res\fR=\fIwidth\fRx\fIheight\fR
.
.IP
