.SH "TMUX SUPPORT"
Utilization of tmux is provided under the command \'chyves \fIguest\fR console tmux\'\.
.
.P
chyves utilizes tmux by creating a session called "chyves", then creates a window named after the guest, then splits that window into two panes\. The left pane is used to manage the guest and the right pane is the serial console for the guest\. If a window named after the guest already exists, then the command is inserted into the active pane for that guest window and then the session is joined or rather \'attached\' in tmux\'s parlance\. Each additional guest has a window created under the same \'chyves\' named session\. See tmux(1) for full details on use\.
.
.P
To use a command for tmux, enter: \'Ctrl + b (release\-keys) \fIcommand\fR\'\. Where Ctrl + b is the modifier, (release\-keys) is literally releasing the Ctrl and b keys, and \fIcommand\fR is the case sensitive letter or command to type in\. Sometimes this is written as \'C\-m\' where \'m\' means modifier\. In this man page, the abbreviated syntax used is \'C\-b\'\. Below are necessary tmux commands for basic use with chyves:
.
.P
While in a tmux session:
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBC\-b n\fR Go to next guest window\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBC\-b p\fR Go to previous guest window\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBC\-b l\fR Go to last guest window\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBC\-b w\fR List all available guest windows and select which to go to\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBC\-b (left\-arrow)\fR Move cursor to the pane to the left
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBC\-b (right\-arrow)\fR Move cursor to the pane to the right
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBC\-b (up\-arrow)\fR Move cursor to the pane above
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBC\-b (down\-arrow)\fR Move cursor to the pane below
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBC\-b c\fR Create a new window
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBC\-b %\fR Split the current pane vertically
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBC\-b "\fR Split the current pane horizontally
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBC\-b x\fR Kill current window
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBC\-b d\fR Detach from tmux session, remains opened in background\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBC\-b D\fR Detach other connections from session\. Good if a session is opened from a smaller resolution client in one location\. Disconnecting it will maximum the screen use on the local connection\.
.
.IP "" 0
.
.P
When not in a tmux session:
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBtmux attach \-t chyves\fR
.
.IP
Reattach to the tmux session named \'chyves\'\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBtmux at\fR
.
.IP
Reattach to the last tmux session
.
.IP "" 0
