.SS "GUEST CLONE SUB\-SUB\-COMMAND"
\fBchyves <guest> clone <clonename>|MG [\-ce|\-cu|\-ie|\-iu] [<pool>]\fR
.
.P
This clones a guest, there are four cloning methods that chyves uses\. The cloning method is determined by the clone flag after the clone name(s)\. The first letter of the flag indicates the clone\'s dependency on the parent\'s datasets, the second letter indicates whether new unique properties are created for the clone\. If the cloning method flag is omitted, the default is used as defined in global property \'default_clone_flag\', this is initially set to \'\-iu\' as it is the safest and more performant\.
.
.P
The \fI[pool]\fR property is used to clone the guest to a different pool than where the guest currently resides\. This can only be done for independent clones\.
.
.P
Dataset dependency:
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB\-c\fR
.
.IP
Creates a ZFS clone of the guest\'s disks\. Initially the clone shares the same blocks as the parent and only a few KB are consumed to point the clone dataset to the parent\'s dataset\. This also means, the clones must be deleted before the parent guest is deleted\. See \'chyves list clones\' to display the clone hierarchy\. The [\fIpool\fR] property is ignored as the clone must reside on the same pool as it\'s parent\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB\-i\fR
.
.IP
Creates an independent clone which is not dependent on the parent\'s datasets\. Using the [\fIpool\fR] property will clone the guest to the specified pool, otherwise the guest\'s pool is used\.
.
.IP "" 0
.
.P
Guest properties:
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB\-e\fR
.
.IP
Copies the guest properties exactly as the parent\'s\. This means the parent can not start while the clone is running, or vise\-versa due to the overlapping serial and tap interfaces\. Use the \'keepnet\' option when deleting these guests to prevent removing the network association\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB\-u\fR
.
.IP
Sets new a unique: serial interface, a new tap is created for each interface of the parent under the same bridge, VALE interfaces are copied over and ports removed, a new unique port is used for uefi_vnc_port, and a new UUID is generated\.
.
.IP
If the guest\'s property \'template\' is set to \'yes\', then the property is temporarily set to \'no\' to create unique properties, then after cloning the guests and clones have their property \'template\' set to \'yes\'\.
.
.IP "" 0
.
.SS "GUEST CONSOLE SUB\-SUB\-COMMANDS"
Manage a guest through a console using various methods described below\. The primary method for managing guests is through a serial interface\. On supported hosts and UEFI guests, video emulation is possible through an internal VNC server attached to a frame buffer\. See \fIUEFI SUPPORT\fR above\. All other guests need to be administered via a serial communication device\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB$null\fR
.
.IP
\fBchyves <guest> console\fR
.
.IP
Establishes a serial connection to a guest using cu(1) via the nmdm(4) device as configure in the \'serial\' property\. To escape the \fBcu\fR connection, press tilde (~) twice, then period (\.), sometimes hitting \fBENTER\fR before that sequence is required\. If that fails to exit the console, try pressing tilde (~), then press Control + d (^d)\. If all else fails then use \'chyves \fIguest\fR console reset\'\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBreset\fR
.
.IP
\fBchyves <guest>|MG console reset\fR
.
.IP
Resets the serial connection for a guest by using \'\fBkill\fR\' against the \fBcu\fR processes associated with the guest as set by the \'serial\' property\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBtmux\fR
.
.IP
\fBchyves <guest>|MG console tmux\fR
.
.IP
Creates a tmux session named chyves, then creates a window named after the guest, and then creates a vertically splits the window with two panes\. The right pane is intended for guest management and the left pane contains the serial interface which is started with \'chyves \fIguest\fR console\'\. See \fITMUX SUPPORT\fR section above\.
.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fBvnc\fR
.
.IP
\fBchyves <guest>|MG console vnc\fR
.
.IP
Requires a UEFI guest that is configured for VNC use on a host that supports UEFI graphics support\. See \fIUEFI SUPPORT\fR above\. Opens a X11 VNC client to the guest using the \fBuefi_vnc_client_*\fR global properties\. See \fIVNC CLIENT SUPPORT\fR section above\.
.
.IP "" 0
.
